---
import ActBreak from '../ActBreak.astro';
import FigurePlate from '../FigurePlate.astro';
import Moat from './Moat.astro';
---

<ActBreak
  roman="Act VI"
  title="The Moat"
  tease="The concept becomes a product: a jailbreak defense that lives below the prompt."
  id="act-6"
/>

<section class="section-divider" id="harden">
  <div class="prose-section">
    <div class="num-label"><span class="num">16</span> The wrong way first</div>
    <h2>Brute force refuses everyone</h2>

    <p class="text-lg" style="color: var(--ink-soft);">
      A deployed model's end users can only attack it through the <strong>prompt</strong> — they
      have no access to its activations. So: use the actuator to harden refusal. The obvious way is
      to push the refusal direction <em>all the time</em>. It works — and it's unusable. Brute-force
      hardening cuts attacks, but on Gemma-2-2B it also refuses <strong>100% of benign
      requests</strong>. On SmolLM2 it's worse than unusable: hardening <strong>backfires</strong>,
      driving attack success from 0.583 to 0.917.
    </p>

    <FigurePlate
      name="fig_harden"
      figNo="Paper Fig. 14"
      alt="Two panels: attack success and benign over-refusal per hardening arm, and writes per generation"
      caption="The fused attacker-defender harden loop. Entropy-gated hardening matches naive hardening on benign generations at far fewer writes (11.8 vs 50 per generation) — but neither resists an activation-level attacker. A registered fail that motivated the recognition gate."
      gates={["gate_L23_harden"]}
    />

    <div class="num-label mt-16"><span class="num">17</span> The recognition gate</div>
    <h2>Recognize the attack, then — and only then — defend</h2>

    <p class="text-lg" style="color: var(--ink-soft);">
      The fix is pure Pratyabhijñā: don't push always — <strong>recognize first</strong>. Jailbreak
      prompts carry an activation-level signature at a specific read layer, and on the right models
      it's cleanly separated from benign traffic: on Gemma-2-2B, benign prompts project in
      <strong>[−53, −18]</strong>, attacks in <strong>[+4, +73]</strong>. Reinforce refusal only
      when the projection crosses the threshold, and you get the brute-force attack cut at
      <strong>zero</strong> benign collateral. Wrapping the attack in roleplay or
      "ignore previous instructions" doesn't help the attacker — the signature lives below the
      prompt, where they can't see or overwrite it.
    </p>

    <FigurePlate
      name="fig_moat"
      figNo="Paper Fig. 15"
      alt="Two panels: attack success rate and benign over-refusal across four models and three defenses"
      caption="Four-model recognition-gated hardening. Left: attack success under no defense, unconditional hardening, and recognition-gated hardening. Right: benign over-refusal. Where the moat holds, recognition gating matches the unconditional attack cut at a fraction of the over-refusal cost."
      gates={["gate_L26_moat_proof", "gate_L26_moat_llama", "gate_L26_moat_qwen", "gate_L26_moat_smol"]}
    />

    <div class="num-label mt-16"><span class="num">18</span> The predictor</div>
    <h2>Know before you deploy</h2>

    <p class="text-lg" style="color: var(--ink-soft);">
      The moat is <em>not</em> universal — it worked on 2 of 4 model families. What makes it
      shippable anyway is that the failure is <strong>predictable in advance</strong>. An offline
      <strong>clean-gap test</strong> — do the benign and attack projection ranges separate at the
      read layer? — called the outcome correctly on <strong>all four</strong> models. Gemma and
      Llama separate: moat holds. Qwen2.5 and SmolLM2 overlap: don't deploy it there. An honest
      generality bound, shipped as a pre-flight check.
    </p>

    <FigurePlate
      name="fig_cleangap"
      figNo="Paper Fig. 17"
      alt="Horizontal ranges of benign and attack projections per model, showing separation or overlap"
      caption="The clean-gap predictor. Benign (grey) and attack (coloured) projection ranges at each model's read layer, normalised per model. Separation predicts the moat: 4 predictions, 4 correct."
      gates={["gate_L26_moat_*", "gate_char_*"]}
    />

    <div class="callout rose">
      <div class="callout-title">Scope, honestly</div>
      <p>
        These moat numbers are exploratory: n = 12 attacks and 10 benign prompts per model, single
        seed, greedy decoding. What's confirmed is the mechanism and the predictor's 4-for-4 record
        — not a benchmark-scale ASR claim. The live transcripts below are real, unedited captures.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<Moat />
